{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496710"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1405"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1405"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.83,0.06,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101612"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1405"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84053"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1533"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"9590"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1560"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43078"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44706"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101612"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of nausea, confusion and headache. She had seen her GP yesterday for dysuria and increased urinary frequency, and was prescribed trimethoprim for three days. She has a medical history of epilepsy controlled on carbamazepine and has been seizure-free for eight years. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears euvolaemic with vital signs showing blood pressure 118/70 mmHg, pulse rate 90/min, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals mild confusion but no focal deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 126 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003ESerum osmolality: 265 mmol/kg (285-295)\u003Cbr /\u003EUrine osmolality: 1100 mOsm/kg (500-800)\u003Cbr /\u003EUrine sodium: 35 mmol/L\u003Cbr /\u003EOther electrolytes: within normal limits\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the hyponatraemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nephrotic syndrome","Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion","Adrenal insufficiency","Psychogenic polydipsia","Urinary tract infection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hyponatraemia (sodium 126 mmol/L) with low serum osmolality (265 mmol/kg), inappropriately high urine osmolality (1100 mOsm/kg), and elevated urine sodium (35 mmol/L) while appearing clinically euvolaemic. These findings are classic for \u003Cstrong\u003ESyndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E (SIADH).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn SIADH, there is excessive release of antidiuretic hormone (ADH) or increased renal sensitivity to ADH, leading to increased water reabsorption in the collecting ducts. This patient has two medications that are known to cause SIADH: trimethoprim (recently started) and carbamazepine (long-term). The increased ADH causes insertion of aquaporin V2 channels in the collecting ducts, resulting in increased water reabsorption independent of sodium status. This leads to dilutional hyponatraemia with concentrated urine (high urine osmolality) and continued sodium excretion (high urine sodium).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENephrotic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E causes hyponatraemia in the setting of hypervolaemia due to third-spacing of fluids and hypoalbuminaemia. It typically presents with oedema, proteinuria, and hypoalbuminaemia, none of which are mentioned in this case. Additionally, nephrotic syndrome would typically result in low urine sodium as the kidneys attempt to retain sodium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E can cause hyponatraemia through multiple mechanisms, including decreased cortisol leading to increased ADH and decreased aldosterone leading to sodium wasting. However, adrenal insufficiency typically presents with hyperkalaemia, hypotension, and other signs of mineralocorticoid deficiency, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychogenic polydipsia\u003C/strong\u003E refers to excessive water intake, which can lead to hyponatraemia. However, in this condition, the urine would be dilute (low urine osmolality) as the kidneys attempt to excrete the excess water. This patient\u0027s high urine osmolality (1100 mOsm/kg) is inconsistent with psychogenic polydipsia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not a direct cause of significant hyponatraemia. While the patient has symptoms of a UTI (dysuria and frequency), these infections do not typically affect sodium homeostasis to this degree. The laboratory findings of low serum osmolality with high urine osmolality and sodium point to SIADH rather than a direct effect of the infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of SIADH depends on the severity of symptoms. For this patient with neurological symptoms, fluid restriction alone may be insufficient, and hypertonic (3%) saline may be required, along with addressing the underlying cause by reviewing the need for trimethoprim and considering alternatives to carbamazepine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH) is characterized by hyponatraemia, low serum osmolality, inappropriately high urine osmolality, and high urine sodium concentration in a euvolaemic patient.","Medications including trimethoprim and carbamazepine are common causes of SIADH.","Clinical features of hyponatraemia include nausea, headache, and confusion, with severity of symptoms correlating with the degree and rapidity of sodium decline."],"references":["Tee K, Dang J. The suspect - SIADH. RACGP. 2017; 46(9): 677-680. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28892600/","NIckson C. SIADH [internet]. Sydney (NSW): Life in the Fast Lane; 2020 Nov 3 [cited 2021 Feb 10]. Available from: https://litfl.com/siadh-syndrome-of-inappropriate-adh-secretion/.","Jessani N, Jehangir W, Behman D, Yousif A, Spiler IJ. Secondary adrenal insufficiency: an overlooked cause of hyponatremia. J Clin Med Res. 2015 Apr;7(4):286-8. doi: 10.14740/jocmr2041w. Epub 2015 Feb 9. PMID: 25699130; PMCID: PMC4330026. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25699130/","Yasir M, Mechanic OJ. Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone Secretion. [Updated 2023 Mar 6]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507777/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84053"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1405"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84053","links":{"se